<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-064-440  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 064 440.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Release 1.0  Dec 31 1989 v89 n12 p10(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EdVenture Holdings 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Groupware: start by automating the familiar.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Work Group ComputingOffice AutomationMultiuser SoftwareOutlookApplicationsUser NeedsTrends.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>GROUPWARE: START BY AUTOMATING THE FAMILIAR These scenarios are typicalmostly in their specificity.andP;  Groupware is not abstract or general.andP;  It's away of automating concrete daily tasks that are routine in their outlines buteach instance different in its own way, so that it takes a constantly varyingcombination of persons and machines to get the work done.andM;In the future, groupware will change how people do their work, but for now itmostly just simplifies it or speeds it up, as described above.andP;  The greatestpotential for a change in process is with Notes and ViewStar, which areprogrammable, potentially active systems as yet used mostly for passiveretrieval and categorization of data.andP;  Users will want more soon enough.andM;(2) Folio gave the AICPA some help with the original data conversion, whenthe Burroughs file was converted into an ASCII text and loaded into Views.andO;Folio built a parser to translate each entry into a Views text item, and toconvert the cross-references into links by recognizing the terminology usedin the book.andP;  It is considering selling the technology to build such parsersas part of a future release.andO;</TEXT></DOC>